cs.NI, cs.GT, cs.SI, cs.CY, cs.CR 

This paper discusses the adoption behavior and offloading benefits of supplementary network technologies in the context of wireless service providers. The paper focuses on the economic principles and impact on technology adoption, which suggests a likely category of cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture). The paper also develops a model for user adoption decisions, which involves game theory and decision-making, indicating a possible category of cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory). Additionally, the paper studies adoption behaviors and revenue-maximizing prices, which could fall under cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) or cs.CY (Computers and Society). Finally, the paper collects empirical data and examines profit-maximizing adoption levels, which suggests a possible category of cs.CR (Cryptography and Security).
